Because even an elected government wouldn’t have any power as countries such as the US don’t recognize Donetsk as it’s own country, an elected government wouldn’t have much power. Despite this, there is a chance that elections are held anyway.

There is a 15% chance that local elections will be held in Donetsk, Ukraine before May 1, 2016; however a 1% chance that these elections will be recognized by other countries. This city has a large population of Pro-Russian citizens and is filled with rebels called coeptis who want Ukraine to return to Russia. Additionally, this city is viewed as a terrorist organization and is not recognized by all countries except Russia as a new country; therefore, other countries will not acknowledge the elections. Due to the close proximity to Russia and its influence, Donetsk, Ukraine will not hold local elections before May 1, 2016.

It seems like the popular opinion in Ukraine is towards holding elections, regardless of whether they are recognized by Ukraine or not. However, it is difficult for Donetsk to organize the resources to hold elections before May.

"Russia’s envoy to the Contact Group Boris Gryzlov hopes for consistent work on the law on election in Donbass and holding the vote in June despite the unsuccessful attempt to coordinate the date in Paris. "The efforts of the Contact Group in the first half of 2016 should be focused on preparing a special law on holding local election in Donbass, as well as organizing an election campaign in the aforementioned timeframe," Gryzlov said"

Most likely elections will be held at some point, but it is highly unlikely that they will be held before May and it is also unlikely they will be acknowledged by other countries as legitimate Even Russian officials who are for the creation of a new pro-Russian government have doubts that these elections will happen anytime soon.

A lot of Ukraine wanted to go away from Russia and become part of the western technology unit. The Russian separatists in Donetsk rioted and separated from Ukraine. I give it a 5% chance because they are such a new country that they will not be recognized as a separate country for a long time.

The citizens in Donetsk decided that they wanted to be able to make decisions for themselves because they intend to split from Ukraine and go over to Russia. Because they believe that the sooner these elections take place the sooner Donetsk will be recognized as a separate entity and thus be able to split from the Ukraine, they are pushing these elections hard. However, Russia, who was the only country backing these elections, put out a statement claiming that they don’t think these elections will happen, implying a very low likelihood of these occurring before May 1. If these elections do end up happening, there is barely any chance that they will be recognized by other governments as the only countries to recognize Donetsk as a separate state are Russia and the Ukraine itself (who view them as a terrorist state and thus wouldn’t back these elections).

There is still a lot of fighting going on in the region, which could make it difficult to organise elections and there is not much time to do so. However, it seems that Russia is keen to look like they are doing everything possible to meet the guidelines set by the Minsk accord and make sure elections are held. http://uatoday.tv/politics/ukraine-rejects-steinmeier-formula-579902.htmlhttp://tass.ru/en/politics/853003 http://m.nasdaq.com/article/relief-for-russias-struggling-economy-cm570760 The Ukrainian population does not want the region to secede, and it is unlikely that the election will be held under perfect conditions, so the Ukrainian government is likely to look for reasons why any election organized before May 1 is illegitimate.

The separatists have scheduled elections for April 20th, not February, I believe. However, Kyiv has not shown a lot of interest in reaching an accommodation on elections for fear these might legitimize Russia's presence there. There are also the issues of fairness and transparency of the voting process (see also: Crimea) as well as whether pro-Ukranian candidates would be allowed to openly participate and campaign. Hard to see a Ukranian-recognized election happening there by April, and if the separatists hold their own elections on April 20th, it could restart fighting.

In realpolitik terms, the conflict in Ukraine really is between the United States and Russia - the Ukrainian government cannot afford to ignore what the United States "requests" - similarly, the self-appointed officials in Donetsk and Lugansk cannot ignore what Moscow demands.

This has some interesting perspective, and I think some persuasive points that Russia, at least, is looking to come to an endgame in the Donbass. http://www.themoscowtimes.com/article/556437.html The appointment of Surkov - who was the principal ideologist of United Russia in the 2000s as it became the ruling party - and the inventor of the notion of "sovereign democracy", and a very close ally of Putin who has also had responsibilities concerning Abkhazia and South Ossetia - to a role concerning the Donbass - is particularly noteworthy.And that of Boris Gryzlov - a senior United Russia official, and long term Duma Chairman - is too. These are really big names for Russia to drop into the conflict. This *might* increase the chance of organizing elections in Donetsk - past experience (in Crimea, as well as in occupied Donetsk and Luhansk) has shown that elections (that lack full democratic scrutiny or process) can be organized fairly quickly - moreover, the elections to the "parliaments" of the two "people's republics" in Donetsk and Luhansk held in late 2014 did not involve the participation of "traditional" or pre-existing parties, only rather more nebulous factions. (This approach has also been seen, to various degrees, in other Russian-sponsored statelets - notably Transnistria, and to an extent Abkhazia.), so there can be expected to be much informality in practice.

Russia is not too happy with much of world to its West, so it would not be surprising if the elections were held. They would definitely not be recognized by Ukraine (much less the rest of of the international community minus China). But at the same time, the elections may be pushed back at the last minute due to "continued negotiations" about the region with all the players.
